# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rocket-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In artificial intelligence (AI), especially machine learning, ablation is the removal of a component of an AI system.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The term is by analogy with biology: removal of components of an organism.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Genetic ablation is another term for gene silencing, in which gene expression is abolished through the alteration or deletion of genetic sequence information.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In cell ablation, individual cells in a population or culture are destroyed or removed.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Both can be used as experimental tools, as in loss-of-function experiments.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In medicine, ablation is the removal of a part of biological tissue, usually by surgery.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Surface ablation of the skin (dermabrasion, also called resurfacing because it induces regeneration) can be carried out by chemicals (chemoablation), by lasers (laser ablation), by freezing (cryoablation), or by electricity (fulguration).
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Its purpose is to remove skin spots, aged skin, wrinkles, thus rejuvenating it.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Surface ablation is also employed in otolaryngology for several kinds of surgery, such as the one for snoring.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The term is also often used in the context of laser ablation, a process in which a laser breaks a material's molecular bonds.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] For a laser to ablate tissues, the power density or fluence must be high, otherwise thermocoagulation occurs, which is simply thermal vaporization of the tissues.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In cardiology, Radiofrequency ablation (RFA) can be used to treat a variety of cardiac arrhythmia such as supraventricular tachycardia, Wolff–Parkinson–White syndrome (WPW), ventricular tachycardia, and more recently as management of atrial fibrillation.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Rotablation is a type of arterial cleansing that consists of inserting a tiny, diamond-tipped, drill-like device into the affected artery to remove fatty deposits or plaque.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The procedure is used in the treatment of coronary heart disease to restore blood flow.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Microwave ablation (MWA) is similar to RFA but at higher frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] High-intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU) ablation removes tissue from within the body noninvasively.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Bone marrow ablation is a process whereby the human bone marrow cells are eliminated in preparation for a bone marrow transplant.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This is performed using high-intensity chemotherapy and total body irradiation.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] As such, it has nothing to do with the vaporization techniques described in the rest of this article.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Ablation of brain tissue is used for treating certain neurological disorders, particularly Parkinson's disease, and sometimes for psychiatric disorders as well.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Recently, some researchers reported successful results with genetic ablation.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In particular, genetic ablation is potentially a much more efficient method of removing unwanted cells, such as tumor cells, because large numbers of animals lacking specific cells could be generated.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Genetically ablated lines can be maintained for a prolonged period of time and shared within the research community.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Researchers at Columbia University report of reconstituted caspases combined from *C. elegans* and humans, which maintain a high degree of target specificity.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The genetic ablation techniques described could prove useful in battling cancer.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Electro-ablation breaks through highly resistive oxide surfaces, such as those found on titanium and other exotic metals and alloys without melting the underlying non-oxidised metal or alloy.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The process is capable of providing surface finishing for a wide range of exotic and widely used metals and alloys, including: titanium, stainless steel, niobium, chromium–cobalt, Inconel, aluminium, and a range of widely available steels and alloys.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Electro-ablation is very effective at achieving high levels of surface finishing in holes, valleys and hidden or internal surfaces on metallic workpieces (parts).
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The process is particularly applicable to components produced by additive manufacturing process, such as 3D-printed metals.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] These components tend to be produced with roughness levels well above 5–20 micron.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Electro-ablation can be used to quickly reduce the surface roughness to less than 0.8 micron, allowing the post-process to be used for volume production surface finishing.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In glaciology and meteorology, ablation—the opposite of accumulation—refers to all processes that remove snow, ice, or water from a glacier or snowfield.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Ablation refers to the melting of snow or ice that runs off the glacier, evaporation, sublimation, calving, or erosive removal of snow by wind.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Air temperature is typically the dominant control of ablation, with precipitation exercising secondary control.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In a temperate climate during ablation season, ablation rates typically average around 2 mm/h.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Where solar radiation is the dominant cause of snow ablation (e.g., if air temperatures are low under clear skies), characteristic ablation textures such as suncups and penitentes may develop on the snow surface.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Ablation can refer to mass loss from the upper surface of a glacier or ocean-driven melt and calving on the face of a glacier terminus.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Ablation can refer either to the processes removing ice and snow or to the quantity of ice and snow removed.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Debris-covered glaciers have also been shown to greatly impact the ablation process.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] There is a thin debris layer that can be located on the top of glaciers that intensifies the ablation process below the ice.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The debris-covered parts of a glacier that is experiencing ablation are sectioned into three categories which include ice cliffs, ponds, and debris.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] These three sections allow scientists to measure the heat digested by the debris-covered area and is calculated.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The calculations are dependent on the area and net absorbed heat amounts in regards to the entire debris-covered zones.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] These types of calculations are done to various glaciers to understand and analyze future patterns of melting.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Moraine (glacial debris) is moved by natural processes that allow for down-slope movement of materials on the glacier body.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] It is noted that if the slope of a glacier is too high then the debris will continue to move along the glacier to a further location.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The sizes and locations of glaciers vary around the world, so depending on the climate and physical geography the varieties of debris can differ.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The size and magnitude of the debris is dependent on the area of glacier and can vary from dust-size fragments to blocks as large as a house.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] There have been many experiments done to demonstrate the effect of debris on the surface of glaciers.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Yoshiyuki Fujii, a professor at the National Institute of Polar Research, designed an experiment that showed ablation rate was accelerated under a thin debris layer and was retarded under a thick one as compared with that of a natural snow surface.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This science is significant due to the importance of long-term availability of water resources and assess glacier response to climate change.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Natural resource availability is a major drive behind research conducted in regards to the ablation process and overall study of glaciers.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Laser ablation is greatly affected by the nature of the material and its ability to absorb energy, therefore the wavelength of the ablation laser should have a minimum absorption depth.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Surface ablation of the cornea for several types of eye refractive surgery is now common, using an excimer laser system (LASIK and LASEK).
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Since the cornea does not grow back, laser is used to remodel the cornea refractive properties to correct refraction errors, such as astigmatism, myopia, and hyperopia.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Laser ablation is also used to remove part of the uterine wall in women with menstruation and adenomyosis problems in a process called endometrial ablation.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Researchers have demonstrated a successful technique for ablating subsurface tumors with minimal thermal damage to surrounding healthy tissue, by using a focused laser beam from an ultra-short pulse diode laser source.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Antifouling paints and other related coatings are routinely used to prevent the buildup of microorganisms and other animals, such as barnacles for the bottom hull surfaces of recreational, commercial and military sea vessels.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Ablative paints are often utilized for this purpose to prevent the dilution or deactivation of the antifouling agent.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Over time, the paint will slowly decompose in the water, exposing fresh antifouling compounds on the surface.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Engineering the antifouling agents and the ablation rate can produce long-lived protection from the deleterious effects of biofouling.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Firestopping and fireproofing products can be ablative in nature.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This can mean endothermic materials, or merely materials that are sacrificial and become "spent" over time while exposed to fire, such as silicone firestop products.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Given sufficient time under fire or heat conditions, these products char away, crumble, and disappear.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The idea is to put enough of this material in the way of the fire that a level of fire-resistance rating can be maintained, as demonstrated in a fire test.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Ablative materials usually have a large concentration of organic matter that is reduced by fire to ashes.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In the case of silicone, organic rubber surrounds very finely divided silica dust (up to 380 m2 of combined surface area of all the dust particles per gram of this dust).
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] When the organic rubber is exposed to fire, it burns to ash and leaves behind the silica dust with which the product started.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Protoplanetary disks are rotating circumstellar disks of dense gas and dust surrounding young, newly formed stars.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Shortly after star formation, stars often have leftover surrounding material that is still gravitationally bound to them, forming primitive disks that orbit around the star's equator – not too dissimilarly from the rings of Saturn.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This occurs because the decrease in the protostellar material's radius during formation increases angular momentum, which means that this remaining material gets whipped into a flattened circumstellar disk around the star.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This circumstellar disk may eventually mature into what is referred to as a protoplanetary disk: a disk of gas, dust, ice and other materials from which planetary systems may form.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In these disks, orbiting matter starts to accrete in the colder mid-plane of the disk from dust grains and ices sticking together.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] These small accretions grow from pebbles to rocks to early baby planets, called planetesimals, then protoplanets, and eventually, full planets.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] As it is believed that massive stars may play a role in actively triggering star formation (by introducing gravitational instabilities amongst other factors), it is plausible that young, smaller stars with disks may be living relatively nearby to older, more massive stars.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This has already been confirmed through observations to be the case in certain clusters, e.g. in the Trapezium cluster.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Since massive stars tend to collapse through supernovae at the end of their lives, research is now investigating what role the shockwave of such an explosion, and the resulting supernova remnant (SNR), would play if it occurred in the line of fire of a protoplanetary disk.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] According to computationally modelled simulations, a SNR striking a protoplanetary disk would result in significant ablation of the disk, and this ablation would strip a significant amount of protoplanetary material from the disk – but not necessarily destroy the disk entirely.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] This is an important point because a disk that survives such an interaction with sufficient material leftover to form a planetary system may inherit an altered disk chemistry from the SNR, which could have effects on the planetary systems that later form.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In spacecraft design, ablation is used to both cool and protect mechanical parts and/or payloads that would otherwise be damaged by extremely high temperatures.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Two principal applications are heat shields for spacecraft entering a planetary atmosphere from space and cooling of rocket engine nozzles.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] Examples include the Apollo Command Module that protected astronauts from the heat of atmospheric reentry and the Kestrel second stage rocket engine designed for exclusive use in an environment of space vacuum since no heat convection is possible.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] In a basic sense, ablative material is designed so that instead of heat being transmitted into the structure of the spacecraft, only the outer surface of the material bears the majority of the heating effect.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The outer surface chars and burns away – but quite slowly, only gradually exposing new fresh protective material beneath.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The heat is carried away from the spacecraft by the gases generated by the ablative process, and never penetrates the surface material, so the metallic and other sensitive structures they protect, remain at a safe temperature.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] As the surface burns and disperses into space, the remaining solid material continues to insulate the craft from ongoing heat and superheated gases.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The thickness of the ablative layer is calculated to be sufficient to survive the heat it will encounter on its mission.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] There is an entire branch of spaceflight research involving the search for new fireproofing materials to achieve the best ablative performance; this function is critical to protect the spacecraft occupants and payload from otherwise excessive heat loading.
[src:rocket-engine/ablation] The same technology is used in some passive fire protection applications, in some cases by the same vendors, who offer different versions of these fireproofing products, some for aerospace and some for structural fire protection.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:rocket-engine/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] The term **acoustic signature** is used to describe a combination of acoustic emissions of sound emitters, such as those of ships and submarines.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] In addition, aircraft, machinery, and living animals can be described as having their own characteristic acoustic signatures or sound attributes, which can be used to study their condition, behavior, and physical location.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] The analysis of acoustic signatures is an important adjunct to passive sonar used to track naval warships and weapons.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] Similar methods have been used to identify aircraft, especially before the development of sophisticated radar tracking.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] The acoustic signature is made up of a number of individual elements.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] These emissions depend on a hull's dimensions, the installed machinery and ship's displacement.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] Therefore, different ship classes will have different combinations of acoustic signals that together form a unique signature.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] Hydrophones and sonar operating in passive mode can detect acoustic signals radiated by otherwise invisible submarines, and use these signals to target attacks.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] Warship designers aim to reduce the acoustic signature of ships and submarines just as much as they aim to reduce the radar cross sections and infra-red signals.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] For submarines, as a prime factor in how they can be detected the reduction of the acoustic signature is a primary goal.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] For a time Britain's Royal Navy toyed with the idea of the trimaran hulled Future Surface Combatant.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] These would have had a very low acoustic signature.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] With three blade-like hulls, these ships would have cut through the water with a minimum of hydrodynamic noise.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] Radiated mechanical noise would also be minimised by using propulsors powered by a diesel-electric power plant, with the diesels being placed in the superstructure to mechanically isolate them from the water.
[src:rocket-engine/acoustic-signature] This project got as far as the construction of the research ship RV Triton to test the principle of a large-scale trimaran design.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:rocket-engine/adiabatic-expansion] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] The AJ-60A rocket motor was developed between 1999 and 2003 for use on the Atlas V.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] On January 19, 2006 the New Horizons spacecraft to Pluto was launched directly into a solar-escape trajectory at 16.26 kilometers per second (58,536 km/h; 36,373 mph) from Cape Canaveral using an Atlas V version with 5 of these SRBs and Star 48B third stage.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] *New Horizons* passed the Moon's orbit in just nine hours.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] In 2015, ULA announced that the Atlas V will switch to new GEM 63 boosters produced by Northrop Grumman Innovation Systems.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] (GEM 63XL, a stretched version of the GEM 63 booster is used on the Vulcan rocket.) The first Atlas V launched with GEM 63 boosters on November 13, 2020.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] AJ-60A is a solid fueled rocket burning HTPB-based composite solid propellant.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] The casing is composed of a graphite-epoxy composite, and the engine throat and nozzle are made of carbon-phenolic composite.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] As configured for use on Atlas V, the nozzle is fixed at a 3 degree cant away from the attachment point, but Aerojet offers a variant with thrust vectoring capability.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] The Atlas V configuration also features an inward slanting nosecone, but it is available with a conventional nosecone or none at all for use on other rockets.
[src:rocket-engine/aj-60a] The stages are designed to be transported by truck.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10** is a hypergolic rocket engine manufactured by Aerojet Rocketdyne (previously Aerojet).
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] It has been used to propel the upper stages of several launch vehicles, including the Delta II and Titan III.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] Variants were and are used as the service propulsion engine for the Apollo command and service module, in the Space Shuttle Orbital Maneuvering System, and on the European Service Module – part of NASA's Orion spacecraft.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The AJ10 engine was first used in the Delta-A/Able second stage of the Vanguard rocket, in the **AJ10-37** configuration.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] It was initially fueled by HNO3 and UDMH.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] An AJ10 engine was first fired in flight during the third Vanguard launch, on 17 March 1958, which successfully placed the Vanguard 1 satellite into orbit.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10-101** engine was used on an uprated version of the Able stage, used on Atlas-Able and Thor-Able rockets.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The first AJ10-101 flight, with a Thor-Able, occurred on 23 April 1958; however, the Thor failed before the upper Able stage fired.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The second flight, which saw the first in flight firing of an AJ10-101 engine, occurred on 10 July 1958.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10-138** engine was originally developed for Vanguard and Able, and was flown from 1964 to 1980.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] Two of these engines were used in the Titan III GTO Transtage, with thrust uprated from 7,800 lbf (35 kN) to 8,000 lbf (36 kN), and with a higher specific impulse of 311 s (3.05 km/s).
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10-137** engine (20,500 lbf (91 kN) of thrust) was used in the Apollo service module's service propulsion system from first flight in 1966.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] Trans-Earth injection, from lunar orbit, was the most critical usage of this engine during the Apollo program.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] This version used Aerozine 50 (a 1:1 mix of UDMH and hydrazine) as fuel and nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer, rather than the previous nitric acid/UDMH.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10-118F** engine produced 9,000 lbf (40 kN) of thrust and was derived from the AJ10-138 engine used on the Transtage.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] It was used by the Delta-F upper stage of the Delta 1000 *Straight Eight* series rocket, starting in 1972.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] This version also used Aerozine 50 as fuel and nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10-190** engine was used on the Space Shuttle Orbital Maneuvering System (OMS) for orbital insertion, on-orbit maneuvers, and de-orbiting, first flown in 1981.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] They produced 26.7 kilonewtons (6,000 lbf) of thrust with a specific impulse (*I*sp) of 316 seconds.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] Following the retirement of the Shuttle, these engines were repurposed for use on the Orion spacecraft's service module.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] This variant uses CH6N2 as fuel, with nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The **AJ10-118K** engine was used on the Delta II rocket's upper stage, Delta-K.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] It used Aerozine 50 as fuel and nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer.
[src:rocket-engine/aj10] The AJ10-118K engine variant was used from 1989 and retired at the conclusion of the ICESat-2 launch on 15 September 2018.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] The **ATREX** engine (**Air Turbo Ramjet Engine with eXpander cycle**) developed in Japan is an experimental precooled jet engine that works as a turbojet at low speeds and a ramjet up to mach 6.0.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] ATREX uses liquid hydrogen fuel in a fairly exotic single-fan arrangement.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] The liquid hydrogen fuel is pumped through a heat exchanger in the air-intake, simultaneously heating the liquid hydrogen and cooling the incoming air.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] This cooling of the incoming air is critical in achieving a reasonable efficiency.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] The hydrogen then continues through a second heat exchanger positioned after the combustion section, where the hot exhaust is used to further heat the hydrogen, turning it in a very high pressure gas.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] This gas is then passed through the tips of the fan providing driving power to the fan at subsonic speeds.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] After mixing with the air, the hydrogen is burned in the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/atrex] The development of this engine lost focus in favor of the new hypersonic precooled turbojet engine (PCTJ).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] A **rocket engine**, also known as a **rocket motor**, is a reaction engine, producing thrust in accordance with Newton's third law by ejecting reaction mass rearward, usually a high-speed jet of high-temperature gas produced by the combustion of rocket propellant stored inside the rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However, non-combusting forms such as cold gas thrusters, nuclear thermal rockets, and ion engines exist.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket vehicles carry their own oxidiser, unlike most combustion engines such as pulse engines or jet engines, so rocket engines can be used in a vacuum, and they can achieve great speed, beyond escape velocity if enough delta V is supplied.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Vehicles commonly propelled by rocket engines include missiles, artillery shells, ballistic missiles, and spaceships.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Compared to other types of jet engines, rocket engines typically have the highest thrust, but are the least propellant-efficient (they have the lowest specific impulse).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For thermal rockets, pure hydrogen, the lightest of all elements, gives the highest exhaust velocity, but practical chemical rockets produce a mix of heavier species, reducing the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Here, "rocket" is used as an abbreviation for "rocket engine".
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket engines produce thrust by the expulsion of gas that has been accelerated to high speed through a nozzle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The fluid is usually a gas created by high pressure (150-to-4,350-pound-per-square-inch (10 to 300 bar)) combustion of solid or liquid propellants, consisting of fuel and oxidiser components, within a combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] As the gases expand through the nozzle, they are accelerated to very high (supersonic) speed, and the reaction to this pushes the vehicle (rocket) in the opposite direction.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Combustion is most frequently used for practical rockets, as the laws of thermodynamics (more specifically Carnot's theorem) dictate that high temperatures and pressures are desirable for the best thermal efficiency.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Nuclear thermal rockets are capable of higher efficiencies, but have low thrust, thanks to the low mass of the propellants used, and also have environmental problems which preclude their routine use in the Earth's atmosphere and cislunar space.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For model rocketry, an available alternative to combustion is a water rocket pressurized by compressed air, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, or any other readily available, inert gas.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket propellant is mass that is stored, usually in some form of tank, or within the combustion chamber itself, prior to being ejected from a rocket engine in the form of a fluid jet to produce thrust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Chemical rocket propellants are the most commonly used.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These undergo exothermic chemical reactions producing a hot jet of gas for propulsion.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Alternatively, a chemically inert reaction mass can be heated by a high-energy power source through a heat exchanger in lieu of a combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Solid rocket propellants are prepared in a mixture of fuel and oxidising components called *grain*, and the propellant storage casing effectively becomes the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Liquid-fueled rockets force separate fuel and oxidizer components into the combustion chamber, where they mix and burn.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Hybrid rocket engines use a combination of solid and liquid or gaseous propellants.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Both liquid and hybrid rockets use *injectors* to introduce the propellant into the chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These are often an array of simple jets – holes through which the propellant escapes under pressure; but sometimes may be more complex spray nozzles.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] When two or more propellants are injected, the jets usually deliberately cause the propellants to collide as this breaks up the flow into smaller droplets that burn more easily.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For chemical rockets the combustion chamber is typically cylindrical, and flame holders, used to hold a part of the combustion in a slower-flowing portion of the combustion chamber, are not needed.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The dimensions of the cylinder are such that the propellant is able to combust thoroughly; different rocket propellants require different combustion chamber sizes for this to occur.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] L* is typically in the range of 64–152 centimetres (25–60 in).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The temperatures and pressures typically reached in a rocket combustion chamber in order to achieve practical thermal efficiency are extreme compared to a non-afterburning airbreathing jet engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] No atmospheric nitrogen is present to dilute and cool the combustion, so the propellant mixture can reach true stoichiometric ratios.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This, in combination with the high pressures, means that the rate of heat conduction through the walls is very high.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In order for fuel and oxidiser to flow into the chamber, the pressure of the propellants entering the combustion chamber must exceed the pressure inside the combustion chamber itself.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This may be accomplished by a variety of design approaches including turbopumps or, in simpler engines, via sufficient tank pressure to advance fluid flow.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The hot gas produced in the combustion chamber is permitted to escape through a narrow space, called the throat, to increase the velocity until it reaches Mach 1, and then continues to accelerate through a diverging expansion section.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] When sufficient pressure is provided to the nozzle (about 2.5–3 times ambient pressure), the nozzle *chokes* and a supersonic jet is formed, dramatically accelerating the gas, converting most of the thermal energy into kinetic energy.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Exhaust speeds vary, depending on the expansion ratio the nozzle is designed for, but exhaust speeds as high as ten times the speed of sound in air at sea level are not uncommon.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] About half of the rocket engine's thrust comes from the unbalanced pressures inside the combustion chamber, and the rest comes from the pressures acting against the inside of the nozzle (see diagram).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] As the gas expands (adiabatically) the pressure against the nozzle's walls forces the rocket engine in one direction while accelerating the gas in the other.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The most commonly used nozzle is the de Laval nozzle, a fixed geometry nozzle with a high expansion-ratio.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The large bell- or cone-shaped nozzle extension beyond the throat gives the rocket engine its characteristic shape.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The exit static pressure of the exhaust jet depends on the chamber pressure and the ratio of exit to throat area of the nozzle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In practice, perfect expansion is only achievable with a variable–exit-area nozzle (since ambient pressure decreases as altitude increases), and is not possible above a certain altitude as ambient pressure approaches zero.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] If the nozzle is not perfectly expanded, then loss of efficiency occurs.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Grossly over-expanded nozzles lose less efficiency, but can cause mechanical problems with the nozzle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Fixed-area nozzles become progressively more under-expanded as they gain altitude.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Almost all de Laval nozzles will be momentarily grossly over-expanded during startup in an atmosphere.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] To maintain this ideal of equality between the exhaust's exit pressure and the ambient pressure, the diameter of the nozzle would need to increase with altitude, giving the pressure a longer nozzle to act on (and reducing the exit pressure and temperature).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This increase is difficult to arrange in a lightweight fashion, although is routinely done with other forms of jet engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In rocketry a lightweight compromise nozzle is generally used and some reduction in atmospheric performance occurs when used at other than the 'design altitude' or when throttled.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] When exhausting into a sufficiently low ambient pressure (vacuum) several issues arise.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] One is the sheer weight of the nozzle—beyond a certain point, for a particular vehicle, the extra weight of the nozzle outweighs any performance gained.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Secondly, as the exhaust gases adiabatically expand within the nozzle they cool, and eventually some of the chemicals can freeze, producing 'snow' within the jet.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This causes instabilities in the jet and must be avoided.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] On a De Laval nozzle, exhaust gas flow detachment will occur in a grossly over-expanded nozzle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] As the detachment point will not be uniform around the axis of the engine, a side force may be imparted to the engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This side force may change over time and result in control problems with the launch vehicle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Advanced altitude-compensating designs, such as the aerospike or plug nozzle, attempt to minimize performance losses by adjusting to varying expansion ratio caused by changing altitude.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For a rocket engine to be propellant efficient, it is important that the maximum pressures possible be created on the walls of the chamber and nozzle by a specific amount of propellant; as this is the source of the thrust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However, speed is significantly affected by all three of the above factors and the exhaust speed is an excellent measure of the engine propellant efficiency.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This is termed *exhaust velocity*, and after allowance is made for factors that can reduce it, the **effective exhaust velocity** is one of the most important parameters of a rocket engine (although weight, cost, ease of manufacture etc. are usually also very important).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For aerodynamic reasons the flow goes sonic ("chokes") at the narrowest part of the nozzle, the 'throat'.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Since the speed of sound in gases increases with the square root of temperature, the use of hot exhaust gas greatly improves performance.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Expansion in the rocket nozzle then further multiplies the speed, typically between 1.5 and 2 times, giving a highly collimated hypersonic exhaust jet.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The speed increase of a rocket nozzle is mostly determined by its area expansion ratio—the ratio of the area of the exit to the area of the throat, but detailed properties of the gas are also important.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Larger ratio nozzles are more massive but are able to extract more heat from the combustion gases, increasing the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Vehicles typically require the overall thrust to change direction over the length of the burn.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets can be further optimised to even more extreme performance along one or more of these axes at the expense of the others.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The most important metric for the efficiency of a rocket engine is impulse per unit of propellant, this is called specific impulse (usually written $I_{sp}$ ).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This is either measured as a speed (the *effective exhaust velocity* $v_{e}$ in metres/second or ft/s) or as a time (seconds).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For example, if an engine producing 100 pounds of thrust runs for 320 seconds and burns 100 pounds of propellant, then the specific impulse is 320 seconds.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The higher the specific impulse, the less propellant is required to provide the desired impulse.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The specific impulse that can be achieved is primarily a function of the propellant mix (and ultimately would limit the specific impulse), but practical limits on chamber pressures and the nozzle expansion ratios reduce the performance that can be achieved.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Since, unlike a jet engine, a conventional rocket motor lacks an air intake, there is no 'ram drag' to deduct from the gross thrust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Consequently, the net thrust of a rocket motor is equal to the gross thrust (apart from static back pressure).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The ${\dot {m}}\;v_{e-opt}\,$ term represents the momentum thrust, which remains constant at a given throttle setting, whereas the $A_{e}(p_{e}-p_{amb})\,$ term represents the pressure thrust term.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] At full throttle, the net thrust of a rocket motor improves slightly with increasing altitude, because as atmospheric pressure decreases with altitude, the pressure thrust term increases.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] At the surface of the Earth the pressure thrust may be reduced by up to 30%, depending on the engine design.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This reduction drops roughly exponentially to zero with increasing altitude.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Maximum efficiency for a rocket engine is achieved by maximising the momentum contribution of the equation without incurring penalties from over expanding the exhaust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Since ambient pressure changes with altitude, most rocket engines spend very little time operating at peak efficiency.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Since specific impulse is force divided by the rate of mass flow, this equation means that the specific impulse varies with altitude.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Due to the specific impulse varying with pressure, a quantity that is easy to compare and calculate with is useful.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets can be throttled by controlling the propellant combustion rate ${\dot {m}}$ (usually measured in kg/s or lb/s).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In liquid and hybrid rockets, the propellant flow entering the chamber is controlled using valves, in solid rockets it is controlled by changing the area of propellant that is burning and this can be designed into the propellant grain (and hence cannot be controlled in real-time).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets can usually be throttled down to an exit pressure of about one-third of ambient pressure (often limited by flow separation in nozzles) and up to a maximum limit determined only by the mechanical strength of the engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For example, some more recent liquid-propellant engine designs that have been optimised for greater throttling capability (BE-3, Raptor) can be throttled to as low as 18–20 per cent of rated thrust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Solid rockets can be throttled by using shaped grains that will vary their surface area over the course of the burn.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket engine nozzles are surprisingly efficient heat engines for generating a high speed jet, as a consequence of the high combustion temperature and high compression ratio.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket nozzles give an excellent approximation to adiabatic expansion which is a reversible process, and hence they give efficiencies which are very close to that of the Carnot cycle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Given the temperatures reached, over 60% efficiency can be achieved with chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For a *vehicle* employing a rocket engine the energetic efficiency is very good if the vehicle speed approaches or somewhat exceeds the exhaust velocity (relative to launch); but at low speeds the energy efficiency goes to 0% at zero speed (as with all jet propulsion).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] See Rocket energy efficiency for more details.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rockets, of all the jet engines, indeed of essentially all engines, have the highest thrust-to-weight ratio.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This is especially true for liquid-fueled rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This high performance is due to the small volume of pressure vessels that make up the engine—the pumps, pipes and combustion chambers involved.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The lack of inlet duct and the use of dense liquid propellant allows the pressurisation system to be small and lightweight, whereas duct engines have to deal with air which has around three orders of magnitude lower density.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Of the liquid fuels used, density is lowest for liquid hydrogen.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket combustion chambers are normally operated at fairly high pressure, typically 10–200 bar (1–20 MPa, 150–3,000 psi).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] When operated within significant atmospheric pressure, higher combustion chamber pressures give better performance by permitting a larger and more efficient nozzle to be fitted without it being grossly overexpanded.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However, these high pressures cause the outermost part of the chamber to be under very large hoop stresses – rocket engines are pressure vessels.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Worse, due to the high temperatures created in rocket engines the materials used tend to have a significantly lowered working tensile strength.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In addition, significant temperature gradients are set up in the walls of the chamber and nozzle, these cause differential expansion of the inner liner that create internal stresses.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] A **hard start** refers to an over-pressure condition during start of a rocket engine at ignition.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In the worst cases, this takes the form of an unconfined explosion, resulting in the damage or destruction of the engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Rocket fuels, hypergolic or otherwise, must be introduced into the combustion chamber at the correct rate in order to have a controlled rate of production of hot gas.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] A "hard start" indicates that the quantity of combustible propellant that entered the combustion chamber prior to ignition was too large.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The result is an excessive spike of pressure, possibly leading to structural failure or explosion.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Avoiding hard starts involves careful timing of the ignition relative to valve timing or varying the mixture ratio so as to limit the maximum pressure that can occur or simply ensuring an adequate ignition source is present well prior to propellant entering the chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Explosions from hard starts usually cannot happen with purely gaseous propellants, since the amount of the gas present in the chamber is limited by the injector area relative to the throat area, and for practical designs, propellant mass escapes too quickly to be an issue.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] A famous example of a hard start was the explosion of Wernher von Braun's "1W" engine during a demonstration to General Walter Dornberger on December 21, 1932.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Delayed ignition allowed the chamber to fill with alcohol and liquid oxygen, which exploded violently.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Shrapnel was embedded in the walls, but nobody was hit.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The extreme vibration and acoustic environment inside a rocket motor commonly result in peak stresses well above mean values, especially in the presence of organ pipe-like resonances and gas turbulence.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The combustion may display undesired instabilities, of sudden or periodic nature.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This may lead to high-amplitude pressure oscillations, often in ultrasonic range, which may damage the motor.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Oscillations of ±200 psi at 25 kHz were the cause of failures of early versions of the Titan II missile second stage engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The other failure mode is a deflagration to detonation transition; the supersonic pressure wave formed in the combustion chamber may destroy the engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Combustion instability was also a problem during Atlas development.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The Rocketdyne engines used in the Atlas family were found to suffer from this effect in several static firing tests, and three missile launches exploded on the pad due to rough combustion in the booster engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In most cases, it occurred while attempting to start the engines with a "dry start" method whereby the igniter mechanism would be activated prior to propellant injection.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] During the process of man-rating Atlas for Project Mercury, solving combustion instability was a high priority, and the final two Mercury flights sported an upgraded propulsion system with baffled injectors and a hypergolic igniter.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The problem affecting Atlas vehicles was mainly the so-called "racetrack" phenomenon, where burning propellant would swirl around in a circle at faster and faster speeds, eventually producing vibration strong enough to rupture the engine, leading to complete destruction of the rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] It was eventually solved by adding several baffles around the injector face to break up swirling propellant.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] More significantly, combustion instability was a problem with the Saturn F-1 engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Some of the early units tested exploded during static firing, which led to the addition of injector baffles.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In the Soviet space program, combustion instability also proved a problem on some rocket engines, including the RD-107 engine used in the R-7 family and the RD-216 used in the R-14 family, and several failures of these vehicles occurred before the problem was solved.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Soviet engineering and manufacturing processes never satisfactorily resolved combustion instability in larger RP-1/LOX engines, so the RD-171 engine used to power the Zenit family still used four smaller thrust chambers fed by a common engine mechanism.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The combustion instabilities can be provoked by remains of cleaning solvents in the engine (e.g. the first attempted launch of a Titan II in 1962), reflected shock wave, initial instability after ignition, explosion near the nozzle that reflects into the combustion chamber, and many more factors.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In stable engine designs the oscillations are quickly suppressed; in unstable designs they persist for prolonged periods.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Oscillation suppressors are commonly used.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] A low frequency oscillation in chamber pressure below 200 Hertz.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Usually it is caused by pressure variations in feed lines due to variations in acceleration of the vehicle, when rocket engines are building up thrust, are shut down or are being throttled.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Chugging can cause a worsening feedback loop, as cyclic variation in thrust causes longitudinal vibrations to travel up the rocket, causing the fuel lines to vibrate, which in turn do not deliver propellant smoothly into the engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This phenomenon is known as "pogo oscillations" or "pogo", named after the pogo stick.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In the worst case, this may result in damage to the payload or vehicle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Chugging can be minimised by using several methods, such as installing energy-absorbing devices on feed lines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] An intermediate frequency oscillation in chamber pressure between 200 and 1000 Hertz.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Usually caused due to insufficient pressure drop across the injectors.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] It generally is mostly annoying, rather than being damaging.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Buzzing is known to have adverse effects on engine performance and reliability, primarily as it causes material fatigue.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In extreme cases combustion can end up being forced backwards through the injectors – this can cause explosions with monopropellants.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] A high frequency oscillation in chamber pressure above 1000 Hertz, sometimes called screaming or squealing.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The most immediately damaging, and the hardest to control.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Acoustic oscillations can be excited by thermal processes, such as the flow of hot air through a pipe or combustion in a chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Specifically, standing acoustic waves inside a chamber can be intensified if combustion occurs more intensely in regions where the pressure of the acoustic wave is maximal.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Such effects are very difficult to predict analytically during the design process, and have usually been addressed by expensive, time-consuming and extensive testing, combined with trial and error remedial correction measures.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Screeching is often dealt with by detailed changes to injectors, changes in the propellant chemistry, vaporising the propellant before injection or use of Helmholtz dampers within the combustion chambers to change the resonant modes of the chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For all but the very smallest sizes, rocket exhaust compared to other engines is generally very noisy.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] As the hypersonic exhaust mixes with the ambient air, shock waves are formed.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The Space Shuttle generated over 200 dB(A) of noise around its base.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] To reduce this, and the risk of payload damage or injury to the crew atop the stack, the mobile launcher platform was fitted with a Sound Suppression System that sprayed 1.1 million litres (290,000 US gal) of water around the base of the rocket in 41 seconds at launch time.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Using this system kept sound levels within the payload bay to 142 dB.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The sound intensity from the shock waves generated depends on the size of the rocket and on the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Such shock waves seem to account for the characteristic crackling and popping sounds produced by large rocket engines when heard live.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These noise peaks typically overload microphones and audio electronics, and so are generally weakened or entirely absent in recorded or broadcast audio reproductions.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For large rockets at close range, the acoustic effects could actually kill.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] More worryingly for space agencies, such sound levels can also damage the launch structure, or worse, be reflected back at the comparatively delicate rocket above.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This is why so much water is typically used at launches.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The water spray changes the acoustic qualities of the air and reduces or deflects the sound energy away from the rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Generally speaking, noise is most intense when a rocket is close to the ground, since the noise from the engines radiates up away from the jet, as well as reflecting off the ground.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Also, when the vehicle is moving slowly, little of the chemical energy input to the engine can go into increasing the kinetic energy of the rocket (since useful power *P* transmitted to the vehicle is $P=F*V$ for thrust *F* and speed *V*).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Then the largest portion of the energy is dissipated in the exhaust's interaction with the ambient air, producing noise.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This noise can be reduced somewhat by flame trenches with roofs, by water injection around the jet and by deflecting the jet at an angle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The development of the US rocket engine industry has been shaped by a complex web of relationships between government agencies, private companies, research institutions, and other stakeholders.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Since the establishment of the first liquid-propellant rocket engine company (Reaction Motors, Inc.) in 1941 and the first government laboratory (GALCIT) devoted to the subject, the US liquid-propellant rocket engine (LPRE) industry has undergone significant changes.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] At least 14 US companies have been involved in the design, development, manufacture, testing, and flight support operations of various types of rocket engines from 1940 to 2000.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In contrast to other countries like Russia, China, or India, where only government or pseudogovernment organisations engage in this business, the US government relies heavily on private industry.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These commercial companies are essential to the continued viability of the United States and its form of governance, as they compete with one another to provide cutting-edge rocket engines that meet the needs of the government, the military, and the private sector.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In the United States the company that develops the LPRE usually is awarded the production contract.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Generally, the need or demand for a new rocket engine comes from government agencies such as NASA or the Department of Defense.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Once the need is identified, government agencies may issue requests for proposals (RFPs) to solicit proposals from private companies and research institutions.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Private companies and research institutions, in turn, may invest in research and development (R&D) activities to develop new rocket engine technologies that meet the needs and specifications outlined in the RFPs.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Alongside private companies, universities, independent research institutes and government laboratories also play a critical role in the research and development of rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Universities provide graduate and undergraduate education to train qualified technical personnel, and their research programs often contribute to the advancement of rocket engine technologies.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] More than 25 universities in the US have taught or are currently teaching courses related to Liquid Propellant Rocket Engines (LPREs), and their graduate and undergraduate education programs are considered one of their most important contributions.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Universities such as Princeton University, Cornell University, Purdue University, Pennsylvania State University, University of Alabama, the Navy's Post-Graduate School, or the California Institute of Technology have conducted excellent R&D work on topics related to the rocket engine industry.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] One of the earliest examples of the contribution of universities to the rocket engine industry is the work of the GALCIT in 1941.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] They demonstrated the first jet-assisted takeoff (JATO) rockets to the Army, leading to the establishment of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However the transfer of knowledge from research professors and their projects to the rocket engine industry has been a mixed experience.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] While some notable professors and relevant research projects have positively influenced industry practices and understanding of LPREs, the connection between university research and commercial companies has been inconsistent and weak.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Universities were not always aware of the industry's specific needs, and engineers and designers in the industry had limited knowledge of university research.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] As a result, many university research programs remained relatively unknown to industry decision-makers.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Furthermore, in the last few decades, certain university research projects, while interesting to professors, were not useful to the industry due to a lack of communication or relevance to industry needs.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Government laboratories, including the Rocket Propulsion Laboratory (now part of Air Force Research Laboratory), Arnold Engineering Test Center, NASA Marshall Space Flight Center, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Stennis Space Center, White Sands Proving Grounds, and NASA John H.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Glenn Research Center, have played crucial roles in the development of liquid rocket propulsion engines (LPREs).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] They have conducted unbiased testing, guided work at US and some non-US contractors, performed research and development, and provided essential testing facilities including hover test facilities and simulated altitude test facilities and resources.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Initially, private companies or foundations financed smaller test facilities, but since the 1950s, the U.S. government has funded larger test facilities at government laboratories.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This approach reduced costs for the government by not building similar facilities at contractors' plants but increased complexity and expenses for contractors.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Nonetheless, government laboratories have solidified their significance and contributed to LPRE advancements.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] LPRE programs have been subject to several cancellations in the United States, even after spending millions of dollars on their development.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For example, the M-l LOX/LH2 LPRE, Titan I, and the RS-2200 aerospike, as well as several JATO units and large uncooled thrust chambers were cancelled.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The cancellations of these programs were not related to the specific LPRE's performance or any issues with it.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Instead, they were due to the cancellation of the vehicle programs the engine was intended for or budget cuts imposed by the government.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Russia and the former Soviet Union was and still is the world's foremost nation in developing and building rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] From 1950 to 1998, their organisations developed, built, and put into operation a larger number and a larger variety of liquid propellant rocket engine (LPRE) designs than any other country.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Approximately 500 different LPREs have been developed before 2003.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For comparison the United States has developed slightly more than 300 (before 2003).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviets also had the most rocket-propelled flight vehicles.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] They had more liquid propellant ballistic missiles and more space launch vehicles derived or converted from these decommissioned ballistic missiles than any other nation.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] As of the end of 1998, the Russians (or earlier the Soviet Union) had successfully launched 2573 satellites with LPREs or almost 65% of the world total of 3973.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] All of these vehicle flights were made possible by the timely development of suitable high-performance reliable LPREs.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Unlike many other countries where the development and production of rocket engines were consolidated within a single organisation, the Soviet Union took a different approach, they established numerous specialised design bureaus (DB) which would compete for development contracts.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Design bureaus which specialised in rocket engines often possessed the necessary personnel, facilities, and equipment to conduct laboratory tests, flow tests, and ground testing of experimental rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Some even had specialised facilities for testing very large engines, conducting static firings of engines installed in vehicle stages, or simulating altitude conditions during engine tests.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] In certain cases, engine testing, certification and quality control were outsourced to other organisations and locations with more suitable test facilities.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Many DBs also had housing complexes, gymnasiums, and medical facilities intended to support the needs of their employees and their families.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviet Union's LPRE development effort saw significant growth during the 1960s and reached its peak in the 1970s.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This era coincided with the Cold War between the Soviet Union and the United States, characterised by intense competition in spaceflight achievements.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Between 14 and 17 Design Bureaus and research institutes were actively involved in developing LPREs during this period.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These organisations received relatively steady support and funding due to high military and spaceflight priorities, which facilitated the continuous development of new engine concepts and manufacturing methods.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Once a mission with a new vehicle (missile or spacecraft) was established it was passed on to a design bureau whose role was to oversee the development of the entire rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This meant that the development or design study of a rocket engine was always aimed at a specific application which entailed set requirements.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] When it comes to which DBs were awarded contracts for the development of new rocket engines either a single design bureau would be chosen or several design bureaus would be given the same contract which sometimes led to fierce competition between DBs.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] When only one DB was picked for the development, it was often the result of the relationship between a vehicle or system's chief designer and the chief designer of a rocket engine specialised DB.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] If the vehicle's chief designer was happy with previous work done by a certain design bureau it was not unusual to see continued reliance on that LPRE bureau for that class of engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] For example, all but one of the LPREs for submarine-launched missiles were developed by the same design bureau for the same vehicle development prime contractor.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However, when two parallel engine development programs were supported in order to select the superior one for a specific application, several qualified rocket engine models were never used.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This luxury of choice was not commonly available in other nations.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However, the use of design bureaus also led to certain issues, including program cancellations and duplication.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Some major programs were cancelled, resulting in the disposal or storage of previously developed engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] One notable example of duplication and cancellation was the development of engines for the R-9A ballistic missile.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Two sets of engines were supported, but ultimately only one set was selected, leaving several perfectly functional engines unused.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Similarly, for the ambitious heavy N-l space launch vehicle intended for lunar and planetary missions, the Soviet Union developed and put into production at least two engines for each of the six stages.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Additionally, they developed alternate engines for a more advanced N-l vehicle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] However, the program faced multiple flight failures, and with the United States' successful Moon landing, the program was ultimately cancelled, leaving the Soviet Union with a surplus of newly qualified engines without a clear purpose.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These examples demonstrate the complex dynamics and challenges faced by the Soviet Union in managing the development and production of rocket engines through Design Bureaus.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The development of rocket engines in the Soviet Union was marked by significant achievements, but it also carried ethical considerations due to numerous accidents and fatalities.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] From a Science and Technology Studies point of view, the ethical implications of these incidents shed light on the complex relationship between technology, human factors, and the prioritisation of scientific advancement over safety.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviet Union encountered a series of tragic accidents and mishaps in the development and operation of rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Notably, the USSR holds the unfortunate distinction of having experienced more injuries and deaths resulting from liquid propellant rocket engine (LPRE) accidents than any other country.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] These incidents brought into question the ethical considerations surrounding the development, testing, and operational use of rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] One of the most notable disasters occurred in 1960 when the R-16 ballistic missile suffered a catastrophic accident on the launchpad at the Tyuratam launch facility.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This incident resulted in the deaths of 124 engineers and military personnel, including Marshal M.I.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] Nedelin, a former deputy minister of defence.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The explosion occurred after the second-stage rocket engine suddenly ignited, causing the fully loaded missile to disintegrate.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The explosion resulted from the ignition and explosion of the mixed hypergolic propellants, consisting of nitric acid with additives and UDMH (unsymmetrical dimethylhydrazine).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] While the immediate cause of the 1960 accident was attributed to a lack of protective circuits in the missile control unit, the ethical considerations surrounding LPRE accidents in the USSR extend beyond specific technical failures.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The secrecy surrounding these accidents, which remained undisclosed for approximately three decades, raises concerns about transparency, accountability, and the protection of human life.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The decision to keep fatal LPRE accidents hidden from the public eye reflects a broader ethical dilemma.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] The Soviet government, driven by the pursuit of scientific and technological superiority during the Cold War, sought to maintain an image of invincibility and conceal the failures that accompanied their advancements.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p01] This prioritisation of national prestige over the well-being and safety of workers raises questions about the ethical responsibility of the state and the organisations involved.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines are usually statically tested at a test facility before being put into production.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] For high altitude engines, either a shorter nozzle must be used, or the rocket must be tested in a large vacuum chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket vehicles have a reputation for unreliability and danger; especially catastrophic failures.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Contrary to this reputation, carefully designed rockets can be made arbitrarily reliable.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In military use, rockets are not unreliable.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] However, one of the main non-military uses of rockets is for orbital launch.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In this application, the premium has typically been placed on minimum weight, and it is difficult to achieve high reliability and low weight simultaneously.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In addition, if the number of flights launched is low, there is a very high chance of a design, operations or manufacturing error causing destruction of the vehicle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The Rocketdyne H-1 engine, used in a cluster of eight in the first stage of the Saturn I and Saturn IB launch vehicles, had no catastrophic failures in 152 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The Pratt and Whitney RL10 engine, used in a cluster of six in the Saturn I second stage, had no catastrophic failures in 36 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The Rocketdyne F-1 engine, used in a cluster of five in the first stage of the Saturn V, had no failures in 65 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The Rocketdyne J-2 engine, used in a cluster of five in the Saturn V second stage, and singly in the Saturn IB second stage and Saturn V third stage, had no catastrophic failures in 86 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster, used in pairs, caused one notable catastrophic failure in 270 engine-flights.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The RS-25, used in a cluster of three, flew in 46 refurbished engine units.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] These made a total of 405 engine-flights with no catastrophic in-flight failures.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] A single in-flight RS-25 engine failure occurred during Space Shuttle *Challenger*'s STS-51-F mission.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This failure had no effect on mission objectives or duration.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] For efficiency reasons, higher temperatures are desirable, but materials lose their strength if the temperature becomes too high.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rockets run with combustion temperatures that can reach 6,000 °F (3,300 °C; 3,600 K).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Most other jet engines have gas turbines in the hot exhaust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Due to their larger surface area, they are harder to cool and hence there is a need to run the combustion processes at much lower temperatures, losing efficiency.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In addition, duct engines use air as an oxidant, which contains 78% largely unreactive nitrogen, which dilutes the reaction and lowers the temperatures.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rockets have none of these inherent combustion temperature limiters.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The temperatures reached by combustion in rocket engines often substantially exceed the melting points of the nozzle and combustion chamber materials (about 1,200 K for copper).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Most construction materials will also combust if exposed to high temperature oxidiser, which leads to a number of design challenges.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The nozzle and combustion chamber walls must not be allowed to combust, melt, or vaporize (sometimes facetiously termed an "engine-rich exhaust").
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rockets that use common construction materials such as aluminium, steel, nickel or copper alloys must employ cooling systems to limit the temperatures that engine structures experience.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Regenerative cooling, where the propellant is passed through tubes around the combustion chamber or nozzle, and other techniques, such as film cooling, are employed to give longer nozzle and chamber life.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] These techniques ensure that a gaseous thermal boundary layer touching the material is kept below the temperature which would cause the material to catastrophically fail.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Material exceptions that can sustain rocket combustion temperatures to a certain degree are carbon–carbon materials and rhenium, although both are subject to oxidation under certain conditions.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Other refractory alloys, such as alumina, molybdenum, tantalum or tungsten have been tried, but were given up on due to various issues.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Materials technology, combined with the engine design, is a limiting factor in chemical rockets.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In rockets, the heat fluxes that can pass through the wall are among the highest in engineering; fluxes are generally in the range of 0.8–80 MW/m2 (0.5–50 BTU/in2-sec).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The strongest heat fluxes are found at the throat, which often sees twice that found in the associated chamber and nozzle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This is due to the combination of high speeds (which gives a very thin boundary layer), and although lower than the chamber, the high temperatures seen there.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] (See § Nozzle above for temperatures in nozzle).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Radiative cooling: The engine is made of one or several refractory materials, which take heat flux until its outer thrust chamber wall glows red- or white-hot, radiating the heat away.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Dump cooling: A cryogenic propellant, usually hydrogen, is passed around the nozzle and dumped.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This cooling method has various issues, such as wasting propellant.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Regenerative cooling: The fuel (and possibly, the oxidiser) of a liquid rocket engine is routed around the nozzle before being injected into the combustion chamber or preburner.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This is the most widely applied method of rocket engine cooling.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Film cooling: The engine is designed with rows of multiple orifices lining the inside wall through which additional propellant is injected, cooling the chamber wall as it evaporates.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This method is often used in cases where the heat fluxes are especially high, likely in combination with regenerative cooling.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] A more efficient subtype of film cooling is transpiration cooling, in which propellant passes through a porous inner combustion chamber wall and transpirates.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] So far, this method has not seen usage due to various issues with this concept.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines may also use several cooling methods.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In all cases, another effect that aids in cooling the rocket engine chamber wall is a thin layer of combustion gases (a boundary layer) that is notably cooler than the combustion temperature.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Disruption of the boundary layer may occur during cooling failures or combustion instabilities, and wall failure typically occurs soon after.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] With regenerative cooling a second boundary layer is found in the coolant channels around the chamber.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This boundary layer thickness needs to be as small as possible, since the boundary layer acts as an insulator between the wall and the coolant.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This may be achieved by making the coolant velocity in the channels as high as possible.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Liquid-fuelled engines are often run fuel-rich, which lowers combustion temperatures.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This reduces heat loads on the engine and allows lower cost materials and a simplified cooling system.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This can also *increase* performance by lowering the average molecular weight of the exhaust and increasing the efficiency with which combustion heat is converted to kinetic exhaust energy.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket propellants require a high energy per unit mass (specific energy), which must be balanced against the tendency of highly energetic propellants to spontaneously explode.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Assuming that the chemical potential energy of the propellants can be safely stored, the combustion process results in a great deal of heat being released.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] A significant fraction of this heat is transferred to kinetic energy in the engine nozzle, propelling the rocket forward in combination with the mass of combustion products released.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Ideally all the reaction energy appears as kinetic energy of the exhaust gases, as exhaust velocity is the single most important performance parameter of an engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] However, real exhaust species are molecules, which typically have translation, vibrational, and rotational modes with which to dissipate energy.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Of these, only translation can do useful work to the vehicle, and while energy does transfer between modes this process occurs on a timescale far in excess of the time required for the exhaust to leave the nozzle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The more chemical bonds an exhaust molecule has, the more rotational and vibrational modes it will have.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Consequently, it is generally desirable for the exhaust species to be as simple as possible, with a diatomic molecule composed of light, abundant atoms such as H2 being ideal in practical terms.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] However, in the case of a chemical rocket, hydrogen is a reactant and reducing agent, not a product.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] An oxidizing agent, most typically oxygen or an oxygen-rich species, must be introduced into the combustion process, adding mass and chemical bonds to the exhaust species.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] An additional advantage of light molecules is that they may be accelerated to high velocity at temperatures that can be contained by currently available materials - the high gas temperatures in rocket engines pose serious problems for the engineering of survivable motors.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] When computing the specific reaction energy of a given propellant combination, the entire mass of the propellants (both fuel and oxidiser) must be included.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The exception is in the case of air-breathing engines, which use atmospheric oxygen and consequently have to carry less mass for a given energy output.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Fuels for car or turbojet engines have a much better effective energy output per unit mass of propellant that must be carried, but are similar per unit mass of fuel.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Computer programs that predict the performance of propellants in rocket engines are available.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] With liquid and hybrid rockets, immediate ignition of the propellants as they first enter the combustion chamber is essential.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Ignition can be achieved by a number of different methods; a pyrotechnic charge can be used, a plasma torch can be used, or electric spark ignition may be employed.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Some fuel/oxidiser combinations ignite on contact (hypergolic), and non-hypergolic fuels can be "chemically ignited" by priming the fuel lines with hypergolic propellants (popular in Russian engines).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Gaseous propellants generally will not cause hard starts, with rockets the total injector area is less than the throat thus the chamber pressure tends to ambient prior to ignition and high pressures cannot form even if the entire chamber is full of flammable gas at ignition.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Solid propellants are usually ignited with one-shot pyrotechnic devices and combustion usually proceeds through total consumption of the propellants.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Once ignited, rocket chambers are self-sustaining and igniters are not needed and combustion usually proceeds through total consumption of the propellants.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Indeed, chambers often spontaneously reignite if they are restarted after being shut down for a few seconds.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Unless designed for re-ignition, when cooled, many rockets cannot be restarted without at least minor maintenance, such as replacement of the pyrotechnic igniter or even refueling of the propellants.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket jets vary depending on the rocket engine, design altitude, altitude, thrust and other factors.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Carbon-rich exhausts from kerosene-based fuels such as RP-1 are often orange in colour due to the black-body radiation of the unburnt particles, in addition to the blue Swan bands.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Peroxide oxidiser-based rockets and hydrogen rocket jets contain largely steam and are nearly invisible to the naked eye but shine brightly in the ultraviolet and infrared ranges.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Jets from solid-propellant rockets can be highly visible, as the propellant frequently contains metals such as elemental aluminium which burns with an orange-white flame and adds energy to the combustion process.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines which burn liquid hydrogen and oxygen will exhibit a nearly transparent exhaust, due to it being mostly superheated steam (water vapour), plus some unburned hydrogen.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The nozzle is usually over-expanded at sea level, and the exhaust can exhibit visible shock diamonds through a schlieren effect caused by the incandescence of the exhaust gas.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The shape of the jet varies for a fixed-area nozzle as the expansion ratio varies with altitude: at high altitude all rockets are grossly under-expanded, and a quite small percentage of exhaust gases actually end up expanding forwards.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The solar thermal rocket would make use of solar power to directly heat reaction mass, and therefore does not require an electrical generator as most other forms of solar-powered propulsion do.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] A solar thermal rocket only has to carry the means of capturing solar energy, such as concentrators and mirrors.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The heated propellant is fed through a conventional rocket nozzle to produce thrust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The engine thrust is directly related to the surface area of the solar collector and to the local intensity of the solar radiation and inversely proportional to the *I*sp.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Nuclear propulsion includes a wide variety of propulsion methods that use some form of nuclear reaction as their primary power source.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] According to the writings of the Roman Aulus Gellius, the earliest known example of jet propulsion was in c.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] 400 BC, when a Greek Pythagorean named Archytas propelled a wooden bird along wires using steam.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] However, it was not powerful enough to take off under its own thrust.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The *aeolipile* described in the first century BC, often known as *Hero's engine*, consisted of a pair of steam rocket nozzles mounted on a bearing.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] It was created almost two millennia before the Industrial Revolution but the principles behind it were not well understood, and it was not developed into a practical power source.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The availability of black powder to propel projectiles was a precursor to the development of the first solid rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Ninth-century Chinese Taoist alchemists discovered black powder in a search for the elixir of life; this accidental discovery led to fire arrows which were the first rocket engines to leave the ground.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] It is stated that "the reactive forces of incendiaries were probably not applied to the propulsion of projectiles prior to the 13th century".
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] A turning point in rocket technology emerged with a short manuscript entitled *Liber Ignium ad Comburendos Hostes* (abbreviated as *The Book of Fires*).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The manuscript is composed of recipes for creating incendiary weapons from the mid-eighth to the end of the thirteenth centuries—two of which are rockets.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The first recipe calls for one part of colophonium and sulfur added to six parts of saltpeter (potassium nitrate) dissolved in laurel oil, then inserted into hollow wood and lit to "fly away suddenly to whatever place you wish and burn up everything".
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The second recipe combines one pound of sulfur, two pounds of charcoal, and six pounds of saltpeter—all finely powdered on a marble slab.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This powder mixture is packed firmly into a long and narrow case.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The introduction of saltpeter into pyrotechnic mixtures connected the shift from hurled Greek fire into self-propelled rocketry.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Articles and books on the subject of rocketry appeared increasingly from the fifteenth through seventeenth centuries.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In the sixteenth century, German military engineer Conrad Haas (1509–1576) wrote a manuscript which introduced the construction of multi-staged rockets.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Rocket engines were also put in use by Tippu Sultan, the king of Mysore.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] These usually consisted of a tube of soft hammered iron about 8 in (20 cm) long and 1+1⁄2–3 in (3.8–7.6 cm) diameter, closed at one end, packed with black powder propellant and strapped to a shaft of bamboo about 4 ft (120 cm) long.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] A rocket carrying about one pound of powder could travel almost 1,000 yards (910 m).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] These 'rockets', fitted with swords, would travel several meters in the air before coming down with sword edges facing the enemy.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] These were used very effectively against the British empire.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Slow development of this technology continued up to the later 19th century, when Russian Konstantin Tsiolkovsky first wrote about liquid-fuelled rocket engines.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] He was the first to develop the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation, though it was not published widely for some years.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The modern solid- and liquid-fuelled engines became realities early in the 20th century, thanks to the American physicist Robert Goddard.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Goddard was the first to use a De Laval nozzle on a solid-propellant (gunpowder) rocket engine, doubling the thrust and increasing the efficiency by a factor of about twenty-five.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] This was the birth of the modern rocket engine.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] He calculated from his independently derived rocket equation that a reasonably sized rocket, using solid fuel, could place a one-pound payload on the Moon.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Goddard began to use liquid propellants in 1921, and in 1926 became the first to launch a liquid-fuelled rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Goddard pioneered the use of the De Laval nozzle, lightweight propellant tanks, small light turbopumps, thrust vectoring, the smoothly-throttled liquid fuel engine, regenerative cooling, and curtain cooling.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] During the late 1930s, German scientists, such as Wernher von Braun and Hellmuth Walter, investigated installing liquid-fuelled rockets in military aircraft (Heinkel He 112, He 111, He 176 and Messerschmitt Me 163).
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The turbopump was employed by German scientists in World War II.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Until then cooling the nozzle had been problematic, and the A4 ballistic missile used dilute alcohol for the fuel, which reduced the combustion temperature sufficiently.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Staged combustion (*Замкнутая схема*) was first proposed by Alexey Isaev in 1949.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The first staged combustion engine was the S1.5400 used in the Soviet planetary rocket, designed by Melnikov, a former assistant to Isaev.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] About the same time (1959), Nikolai Kuznetsov began work on the closed cycle engine NK-9 for Korolev's orbital ICBM, GR-1.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Kuznetsov later evolved that design into the NK-15 and NK-33 engines for the unsuccessful Lunar N1 rocket.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] In the West, the first laboratory staged-combustion test engine was built in Germany in 1963, by Ludwig Boelkow.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Liquid hydrogen engines were first successfully developed in America: the RL-10 engine first flew in 1962.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] Its successor, the Rocketdyne J-2, was used in the Apollo program's Saturn V rocket to send humans to the Moon.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The high specific impulse and low density of liquid hydrogen lowered the upper stage mass and the overall size and cost of the vehicle.
[src:rocket-engine/rocket-engine-p02] The record for most engines on one rocket flight is 44, set by NASA in 2016 on a Black Brant.
